Study Description: CTA Abdomen Pelvis
Attending Physician: APRN-SUR Raymond Li
Ordering Physician: APRN-SUR Raymond Li
Referring Physician: APRN-SUR Raymond Li
Primary Care Physician: APRN-SUR Raymond Li
INDICATION:
52-year-old with history of AAA repair 2022-08-29, no complaints, follow-up
TECHNIQUE:
CT angiogram of the abdomen and pelvis with and without contrast. 3-D reformatted
images were acquired. Radiation dose reduction techniques included automated exposure
control or exposure modulation based on body size.
COMPARISON:
July 21st 2021.
FINDINGS:
The soft tissues are remarkable for prior venipuncture and surgical changes involving
the left inguinal region. There are no acute nor destructive osseous lesions. The lung
bases are clear. The heart is enlarged and there is no pericardial nor pleural
effusion. There is no inflammatory change, abscess, free air, significant free fluid
or pathologically enlarged lymphadenopathy. The liver is low-density relative to the
spleen consistent with fatty infiltration and there are no renal stones bilaterally
nor is there hydroureteronephrosis to the pelvis. The large and small bowel
demonstrate normal caliber with a nonacute pattern. Both the terminal ileum and the
appendix are normal. The unenhanced liver demonstrates no focal lesions. The
gallbladder, spleen, adrenals, right kidney and pancreas are unremarkable and
unchanged. There is some persistent left renal atrophy and perinephric stranding
similar to the previous. There is a new aortic endograft is well opacified. The
infrarenal abdominal aortic aneurysm has decreased to 4.3 cm. There is no contrast or
enhancement within the excluded triple lumen.
IMPRESSION:
4.3 cm fusiform infrarenal AAA decreased from 4.4 cm. There is a new widely opacified
aortic endograft.
Subtle fatty liver
Left renal atrophy similar to the previous
